item.title: Artillery X2 - Genius Pro Bl touch mount (waggster)
item.description:
A quick remix of the X2 waggster fan shroud mount by Dannsantos (Thanks for doing it) to take off the fan shroud allowing the use of the original fan and replacment BL touch or 3d touch on the X2 or Genius Pro. This will fit the X2 / Genius Pro and allow the blue plastic cover to be used.

printed with support from bed. 70% infill.
You will need to change the offset for the BL touch.
That is relatively simple.
Download Prontaface, use the blue cable from the black bag. connect cable to computer and the side of the printer, the printer will start (using the 5v rom the usb) check the com port top left on Prontaface and change connection to 115200. connect to printer. on right side it will say connected.

M851 X28 Y-33
then type M500 to save it to eeprom.
then M501 use active parameters
That will be the new BL touch flashed into eeprom

basic Youtube about setting up Prontaface; https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sbIwHGrOzUM
item.author: thaicbr

item.title: Texas Instruments Calculator Front Covers (TI-84 Plus, TI-84 Plus C, TI-90 Titanium, and similar)
item.description:
I needed a replacement cover for a TI-89 Titanium edition that I was selling on Facebook marketplace, so that the buyer would be satisfied. Luckily, I had another TI-84 calculator that still had its original cover so I could recreate one for my TI-89.

All of the measurements in this post are my own, so they could be not exact to the original part, but the printed part still works splendidly. I am going to include them, a short explanation, and the model files so you can more easily modify/make your own. It would be cool to see a TI calculator cover that had a hinge so the front cover folded open rather than coming entirely off.

The key measurements include:

For the rail/slot cross section profile

The distance from the calculator front keys to the to the far side of the cover slot.
    12.7 mm (0.50 in)
The size of the cover rail slot on the calculator.
    2.0 mm (0.079 in)
The depth of the cover rail slot on the calculator.
    1.27 mm (0.05 in)
The width of the calculator (from left to right).
    84 mm (3.31 in)
Rail start from bottom of the case ~40 mm and a rail length of 79 mm.

For the case profile

The distance from foot to head on the front of the calculator
    187 mm (7.36 in)
The curvature of the calculator side cross section
    Measured to be 10 mm (0.39 in).
The curvature of the calculator foot front cross section.
    Assumed tangent to both edges, and measured a foot horizontal length of 34 mm (1.34 in).

I created a rectangular profile with an offset from the calculator body of 0.2 mm, and designed a rail from the side of the rectangular profile with similar tolerances and a 60 degree angle so that it would not need supports.

I went with a 2.2 mm shell thickness. I also created one with an angular side profile so all support are eliminated by not having the curved 10 mm surface.

EDIT

Later, I found a TI-84 model on GrabCad so I am linking it here. There is also a case on there I saw too, but I did not like it very much.
item.author: Ostella3d

item.title: RC Plane snow Ski
item.description:
Skis for your planes so you can fly in the frozen winter! I live in Maine, so flying in the winter time means snow. Obviously, skis had to happen. I've tweaked these to the point that I'm pretty happy with them. They look scale-ish and fly well. The only thing I'd say is that when landing, you might need more up elevator than you're used to.

They are designed to be held on with rubber bands over the wheels ans "sprung" with either a cut rubber band or elastic thread for the front and back to keep the skis at the correct attitude. Be sure to take them off when you're done flying so the rubber bands don't deform your tires.

I printed these in PEGP but I can't see how it wouldn't work in PLA. Supports are only for the lugs that the rubber bands fit over to keep it on the wheel. I've been flying with these for two winters now and they work really well. These were designed to fit 70mmx20mm wheels (2.75 in x .75 in) but can be scaled easily to fit smaller wheels.

item.title: Sydney City cityscape with topography- 16 tiles
item.description:
Plesase note I am yet to print this myself but have tested slicing each individual tile and it slices fine. You will need to add a model of the Harbour Bridge. there are numerous free models to choose from on Thingiverse.

I created this using OpenStreetData. © OpenStreetMap contributors. data is available under the Open Database License. https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright

I am very new to this space and only follwed youtube tutorials, any tips and hints welcome. Please analyse closely before printing. I have scaled all tiles equally and up 150% to exaggerate the buildings, you may want to scale them down. All tiles are made to fit on a standard ender 3 v2 bed. You may need to orient them in cura to make them fit but they all do.

I created this because I am tight and didn't want to pay someone for it. There were no detailed free versions I could find. Enjoy

item.title: Yeti 14 oz Rambler Adapter for 2017 Toyota Tacoma Center Console Middle Cup Holder
item.description:
A family member wanted an adapter for their cup holder so that it could hold their 14 oz Yeti Rambler and its hot coffee safe during their morning commute.

A lot of the existing designs did not allow for printing without supports or limited how the cup could be oriented.

This design hopes to solve that by making it easy to print and easy to place the cup. Designed with a 0.4 mm nozzle in mind with a wall thickness of 4.8 mm. The handle slot number can be increased, but i recommend around 7 as a max. 60degree overhangs max.

This model works well for the center console cup holder of a 2017 Toyota Tacoma, but may work well with other cup holders that have a ~70 mm bottom ID, ~80 mm top ID, and a 80 mm height. If you try this print and it works well with your car please let me know and I can add it to the list so others can be aware.
Year-Make-Model Cup Holder Location
2017 Toyota Tacoma Middle Center Console
…pending… …pending…

If you want the Yeti Rambler dimensions to make your own accessories, I uploaded it to my profile as a separate print.

IMPORTANT!

If you planning on printing these files please be aware of what temperatures can be reached inside your vehicle during the summer months. I would highly recommend printing in PETG rather than PLA.

item.title: Butted Goblin Fairy
item.description:
Have you ever wished you had a little Goblin with a butt to share your space with and look deeply into the eyes of the all knowing? Well your in luck because here it is!

Print it
Look at its butt
Be happy!

Recommendations for printing:

Super straight forward, prints without supports. I would recommend dialing in your retraction settings, and making sure your filament is dry for the horns to come out well!

Also if your slicing in Cura and printing at 100%, enabling the setting "filter out tiny gaps" will help print the horns smoother, not sure if this still applies once it is resized.

Enjoy!
